PART A — GIOP HISTORICAL CHRONOLOGY

These milestones are not formulas. They are the shoulders on which GIOP
stands. Each entry records the first deployment of a technology now
foundational to modern imaging.

01 Nokia PureView Oversampling (2012)
  First 7:1 superpixel oversampling in a phone. Introduced lossless zoom.
  Formula: R(z) = max(1, R_base / z^2). At 1x, R = 7:1; at max zoom, R = 1:1.
  Significance: Origin of modern pixel binning and computational zoom.

02 Nokia Optical Image Stabilization (2012)
  First hardware floating-lens OIS in a smartphone (Lumia 920).
  Ancestor of every OIS and sensor-shift stabilization system.

03 Nokia Large Sensor and Xenon Flash (2010)
  1/1.83-inch sensor in Nokia N8. First phone to challenge point-and-shoot
  cameras with a large sensor and proper xenon flash.

04 Nokia Carl Zeiss Optics and Autofocus (2005)
  First Carl Zeiss Tessar lens on a phone (Nokia N90). Established the
  optics-first philosophy for mobile imaging.

05 Nokia Dual-Lens Camera (2005)
  First 3G smartphone with front VGA camera (Nokia 6680). Foundation of the
  multi-camera arrays now standard in every device.

06 Panasonic Mobile Autofocus (2003)
  First phone with autofocus CCD sensor (Panasonic mova P505iS). Proved that
  mobile cameras could mechanically focus.

07 Sony 4K Display Ecosystem (2011/2015)
  First true 4K home projector (VPL-VW1000ES, 2011). First 4K smartphone
  display (Xperia Z5 Premium, 2015). Established 4K as a consumer standard.

08 Sony Optical Zoom and Exmor Sensor (2007/2013)
  First folded optical zoom lens in a phone (SO905iCS, 2007). First large
  Exmor RS sensor with BSI in a phone (Xperia Z1, 2013).

09 Huawei Dual Sensor with Leica (2016)
  RGB plus monochrome dual sensor in Huawei P9. Started the computational
  bokeh era and proved dual-sensor fusion could rival larger single sensors.

10 Huawei RYYB Periscope Zoom (2019)
  RYYB color filter array captures 40 percent more light than traditional
  Bayer. First commercial 5x periscope zoom lens (P30 Pro).

11 Honor Integrated Micro-Gimbal (2026)
  4DoF micro-gimbal with AI horizon lock. Mechanical stabilization meets
  predictive electronic stabilization, enabling multi-second handheld
  exposures with zero motion blur.

PART B — CAMERA SETTINGS TOOLKIT

B1. FALSE COLOR IRE ZONES
IRE (Institute of Radio Engineers) scale maps luminance to a percentage
where 0 IRE is black and 100 IRE is reference white.

Formula: IRE = (Luminance / Reference_White) * 100
Reference_White is 90 percent diffuse white in scene-referred space.

Zone mapping for exposure assessment:
  0 to 5 percent IRE (Purple): underexposure, noise floor.
  5 to 15 percent IRE (Blue): deep shadows.
  15 to 25 percent IRE (Cyan): shadows, minimal detail.
  25 to 50 percent IRE (Green): midtones, well-exposed.
  50 to 60 percent IRE (Pink): Caucasian skin tone (approximately 50 IRE).
  60 to 75 percent IRE (Yellow): bright highlights.
  75 to 95 percent IRE (Orange): very bright highlights.
  95 to 100 percent IRE (Red): near clipping.
  Above 100 percent IRE (White): clipped.

B2. CONTRAST FORMULAS
Contrast quantifies the difference between light and dark regions.

Michelson Contrast:
  C = (I_max - I_min) / (I_max + I_min)
Defined for periodic patterns. Range: 0 (uniform) to 1 (maximum).

RMS Contrast:
  C_RMS = sqrt( (1/N) * sum( (I_i - I_mean)^2 ) )
Defined for arbitrary images. Measures standard deviation of pixel
intensities relative to the mean.

S-Curve Contrast (Sigmoid):
  I_out = 1 / (1 + exp(-gain * (I_in - pivot)))
Applies a film-like contrast curve. gain controls steepness, pivot sets
the mid-point. Input and output are scene-referred linear.

B3. SATURATION FORMULAS
Saturation controls the intensity of color relative to its luminance.

HSL Saturation:
  Saturation = (M - m) / M   if M != 0, else 0
where M = max(R,G,B), m = min(R,G,B).

CIELAB Chroma:
  Chroma = sqrt( a*^2 + b*^2 )
Perceptually uniform measure of colorfulness.

Luminance-Preserving Saturation:
  R_out = L + sat * (R_in - L)
  G_out = L + sat * (G_in - L)
  B_out = L + sat * (B_in - L)
where L = 0.2126*R_in + 0.7152*G_in + 0.0722*B_in
sat = 0 yields grayscale; sat = 1 yields original color; sat > 1 enhances.

B4. EXPOSURE TRIANGLE REFERENCE
The fundamental relationship:
  E = k * (t * S) / N^2
where E is exposure at the sensor, t is shutter speed, S is ISO gain,
N is f-number, and k is a calibration constant.

One stop represents a doubling or halving of light.

APEX System:
  Av = 2 * log2(N)
  Tv = -log2(t)
  Sv = log2(ISO / 3.125)
  Ev = Av + Tv = Bv + Sv

Exposure Value at ISO 100:
  EV100 = log2(N^2 / t)

Sunny 16 Rule: on a bright sunny day at ISO 100, set f/16 and 1/ISO seconds.
Handheld Shutter Rule: minimum shutter speed is approximately
  1 / (focal_length * crop_factor) seconds.

PART C — PARAMETER GUARDRAILS AND FAULT TOLERANCE

C1. SAFE OPERATING RANGES
All parameters in the GIOP pipeline have defined safe ranges. Values
outside these ranges trigger warnings or hard stops.

Sensor parameters:
  Quantum Efficiency: 0.0 to 1.0. Values outside trigger fault.
  Full Well Capacity: must be positive. Negative FWC triggers fault.
  Read Noise: must be positive. Zero or negative triggers warning.
  Conversion Gain: must be positive. Non-positive triggers fault.

Lens parameters:
  Distortion coefficients k1, k2, k3: must produce unique mapping
    (no fold-over) over the full sensor area. Fold-over triggers fault.
  Vignetting fall-off: must not exceed 90 percent at any field angle.
    Excessive fall-off triggers warning.
  Chromatic aberration shift: must not exceed 2 pixels at sensor edges.
    Exceeding 3 pixels triggers warning.

Display parameters:
  Peak luminance: 0.0 to 10,000 cd/m^2 for PQ. Values above 10,000 are
    clipped. Negative values trigger fault.
  Black level: 0.0 to peak_luminance. Black level above peak triggers fault.
  EOTF: the ODT must produce code values within the valid range for the
    bit depth (0 to 1023 for 10-bit, 0 to 4095 for 12-bit). Underflow or
    overflow triggers hard clipping and a warning event.

C2. SENSOR FAULT FLAGS
Embedded in RAW metadata, these flags alert downstream processing.

Dead pixel map: a binary map per color channel indicating permanently stuck
  or dead pixels. The ISP or GIOP linearization must interpolate these.
  If more than 0.5 percent of pixels in any channel are flagged, a warning
  is emitted. If more than 2 percent, a fault is raised.

Black level instability: the optical black region's mean value shifts by
  more than 2 digital numbers between consecutive frames. Triggers a warning.
  Shift exceeding 10 DN triggers a fault and the frames are marked as suspect.

Column or row noise: a periodic pattern in the dark frame with amplitude
  exceeding 1.5 times the read noise standard deviation. Triggers warning.

Temperature excursion: sensor temperature exceeding manufacturer maximum
  by more than 5 degrees Celsius. Triggers immediate throttle or shutdown.

C3. DUAL NATIVE ISO CROSSOVER FAULT DETECTION
Dual native ISO systems switch between two analog gain paths at a
calculated crossover point.

Crossover signal level S_x (in electrons):
  S_x = N_read,low^2 / (GC_high / GC_low - 1)
where GC is gain (DN/e-) and N_read,low is the low-gain read noise.

Fault detection logic:
  If the camera reports a dual gain mode but S_x is negative (implies
  GC_high <= GC_low), the system raises a configuration fault.
  If the actual signal at the crossover frame exceeds S_x by more than
  20 percent but high gain remains active, a crossover failure fault
  is raised. The frame is flagged for potential highlight clipping.
  If the actual signal is below 0.8 * S_x but low gain is active, a
  noise-floor fault is raised. The frame is flagged for excessive noise.

C4. ROLLING SHUTTER SKEW TOLERANCE
Rolling shutter introduces geometric distortion in moving scenes.

Skew angle theta with respect to vertical:
  tan(theta) = (vx * t_frame) / (N_rows * pixel_pitch)
where vx is horizontal image-plane velocity in pixels per second, t_frame
is total sensor readout time, N_rows is total row count.

Tolerance limits:
  For cinematic acquisition (24 fps, 180-degree shutter): skew angle must
    not exceed 0.5 degrees. If exceeded, the frame is flagged for VFX
    pipeline review and the skew angle is embedded in metadata.
  For broadcast (50/60 fps): skew angle must not exceed 0.25 degrees.
  For high-speed (100+ fps): skew angle must not exceed 0.1 degrees.
  If skew exceeds 2.0 degrees, the frame is marked as degraded and the
    GIOP runtime raises a warning event.

C5. CLIPPING INDICATORS
The GIOP pipeline monitors for clipping at multiple stages.

Sensor saturation: pixel value equals FWC within 2 percent tolerance.
  Flagged as saturated. Number of saturated pixels per frame is logged.
  If more than 5 percent of the frame is saturated, a highlight warning
  is emitted.

Codec quantization clipping: after encoding and decoding, pixels that
  exceed the original pre-encode value by more than 1 percent are
  flagged as codec overshoot. These are tracked per GOP.

Display clipping: any linear color component exceeding the display peak
  luminance (in cd/m^2 mapped to PQ code value) triggers display clipping
  flag and the ODT clamps to peak.

C6. CONFIGURATION FAULT DETECTION
GIOP runtime validates its own configuration at startup and periodically
during operation.

Checks:
  All referenced LUT files exist and pass hash verification.
  All plugin manifests match their binaries.
  The OCIO config parses without error.
  The display profile matches the connected monitor EDID.
  GPU driver version meets minimum specified in the runtime release notes.

Any check failure raises a fault event. If the fault affects color
fidelity (LUT hash mismatch, plugin cert expired, OCIO parse error),
the runtime enters safe mode: all transforms are bypassed and a magenta
overlay is applied to the viewer until the fault is resolved.

C7. RECOVERY PROCEDURES
When a fault is detected, the runtime follows a documented recovery
sequence.

Transient faults (single frame GPU timeout, IPC delay):
  Frame is reprocessed with bypassed suspect component.
  If reprocessing succeeds, normal operation resumes.
  If three consecutive frames fail, the component is quarantined.

Persistent faults (hash mismatch, plugin crash, config error):
  Faulted component is disabled.
  Identity transform is inserted in its place.
  Event with severity FATAL is emitted.
  Operator must acknowledge the fault before production continues.

All fault events are written to an append-only log with SHA3-512
chaining: each log entry includes the hash of the previous entry,
preventing tampering with the operational history.

